# Epic 1: PAL Foundation — extend the Platform Abstraction Layer for cross-platform truth

## Why this is epic 1

`src/platform/pal.rs` exists today (17 KB) but its surface is incomplete. Most of the codebase still uses `#[cfg(target_os = "linux")]` directly rather than calling through the PAL. Result: adding macOS today would require patching dozens of `cfg` sites. We need to first widen the PAL so all platform-specific behavior funnels through it. Then per-OS impls slot in cleanly.

## Current state (audit findings from 2026-05-03)

```
src/cli_app.rs:1506    #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
src/cli_app.rs:698     if args.systemd && !cfg!(target_os = "linux") { error }
src/core/errors.rs:27  UnsupportedPlatform { details } -> "[SBH-1101]"
src/cli/wizard.rs:179, 283, 550, 590, 813, 949   linux-only branches
src/platform/pal.rs:276-280    Linux fallback returns UnsupportedPlatform on non-Linux
src/daemon/signals.rs:238-251  linux-only signal handling
src/ballast/manager.rs:588, 638  linux-only ballast operations
src/daemon/self_monitor.rs:524-534  linux-only self-monitoring
```

**Conclusion:** ~19+ direct `cfg(target_os = "linux")` sites scattered across code areas. Not all should funnel through PAL — some (like systemd notify) are inherently OS-specific and stay gated. But many *should* be PAL methods returning a normalized type.

## Architectural decision: trait-based PAL with compile-time dispatch

```rust
// src/platform/pal.rs
pub trait Pal: Send + Sync + 'static {
    fn name(&self) -> &'static str;
    fn capacity(&self, mount: &Path) -> Result<Capacity>;
    fn mounts(&self) -> Result<Vec<MountInfo>>;
    fn memory_pressure(&self) -> Result<MemoryPressure>;
    fn process_list(&self) -> Result<Vec<ProcessInfo>>;
    fn process_io(&self, pid: i32) -> Result<ProcessIo>;
    fn open_files(&self, path: &Path) -> Result<Vec<OpenFile>>;
    fn user_home(&self) -> PathBuf;
    fn temp_dirs(&self) -> Vec<PathBuf>;
    fn cache_roots(&self) -> Vec<PathBuf>;
    fn sacred_paths(&self) -> Vec<SacredPath>;
    fn service_kind(&self) -> ServiceKind;  // Systemd | Launchd | None
    // ... extended progressively as later epics need them
}

#[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
pub fn current() -> impl Pal { LinuxPal::new() }

#[cfg(target_os = "macos")]
pub fn current() -> impl Pal { MacOsPal::new() }
```

We use `impl Pal` return + monomorphization rather than `Box<dyn Pal>` because (a) the platform is fixed at compile time, (b) zero-cost is important on the daemon hot path, (c) avoids vtable indirection in tight loops (e.g., scanning thousands of files).

For tests we expose `MockPal` behind `#[cfg(test)]` and use generic functions: `fn scan<P: Pal>(pal: &P, ...)`. Production callers use `pal::current()`; test callers inject `MockPal`.

## Tasks (see child beads)

1. Audit + inventory every `#[cfg(target_os)]` and `cfg!(target_os)` site, classify each: PAL-method-candidate, leave-as-cfg-gate, or refactor-to-trait-method.
2. Define the full `Pal` trait surface (data types + method signatures) up front so subsequent epics target a stable interface.
3. Refactor existing Linux code to implement the new trait via `LinuxPal` — pure mechanical move, no behavior change.
4. Create empty `MacOsPal` skeleton with `unimplemented!()` bodies. Code compiles on macOS.
5. Wire compile-time dispatch in `pal::current()`.
6. Replace SBH-1101 unsupported-platform error with per-method "not yet implemented on this OS" *only* for unimplemented PAL methods. (Most CLI commands no longer fail wholesale on Mac; they fail with specific actionable messages.)
7. Update `core/errors.rs` to carry `(method_name, os_name)` for each unimplemented PAL call so error messages are helpful, not generic.
8. Add a `pal::probe()` diagnostic command (`sbh doctor --pal`) that calls every PAL method and reports which work / which return NotImplemented. Run on every supported OS in CI.

## Why "extend PAL first, implement Mac second" instead of vice versa

If we implement Mac syscalls in scattered `cfg(macos)` blocks alongside the existing `cfg(linux)` blocks, we pay the refactor cost twice (or never — and get stuck with parallel-but-not-equal cfg ladders forever). Doing the PAL widening first means: every Mac implementation just plugs into the trait. It also means future BSD/Windows ports cost 1 PAL impl, not a full code audit.

## Risks

- Trait surface might not be wide enough → discovered later, requires re-refactor. Mitigation: do all 16 sub-epic design docs *first* and feed required PAL methods up to E1 before freezing the trait.
- Performance regression from trait indirection → Mitigation: benchmark hot paths (scanner, monitor poll loop) before/after.
- Breaks Linux while refactoring → Mitigation: every PR runs full Linux test suite; merge Mac work behind a feature flag if needed during transition.

## Success criterion

All `cfg(target_os = "linux")` sites in src/ are either (a) PAL method calls, (b) explicitly gated platform-specific behavior with documented justification (one-liner comment per gate), or (c) replaced with PAL fallback. `grep -r "cfg(target_os" src/ | wc -l` should drop by ≥ 60%.

src/platform/mod.rs gets:

  #[cfg(target_os = "linux")]
  pub fn current() -> impl Pal { linux::LinuxPal::new() }

  #[cfg(target_os = "macos")]
  pub fn current() -> impl Pal { macos::MacOsPal::new() }

  #[cfg(not(any(target_os = "linux", target_os = "macos")))]
  compile_error!("sbh requires Linux or macOS");

Verify generic functions in callers can take `<P: Pal>` and the daemon main loop uses pal::current() exactly once at startup, passing the concrete type via generics.

Why monomorphization not dyn: zero-cost; no vtable indirection; the platform is fixed at compile time so polymorphism would be pure overhead.

