REVIEW: The state file (/var/lib/sbh/state.json) is the PRIMARY mechanism for CLI-to-daemon communication. Its format must be well-defined:

```json
{
  "version": "0.1.0",
  "pid": 12345,
  "started_at": "2026-02-14T10:00:00Z",
  "uptime_seconds": 307342,
  "last_updated": "2026-02-14T15:30:00Z",
  "pressure": {
    "overall": "green",
    "mounts": [
      {"path": "/data", "free_pct": 23.4, "level": "green", "rate_bps": -12400000}
    ]
  },
  "ballast": {"available": 8, "total": 10, "released": 2},
  "last_scan": {"at": "2026-02-14T15:29:55Z", "candidates": 3, "deleted": 0},
  "counters": {"scans": 1542, "deletions": 312, "bytes_freed": 467800000000, "errors": 2}
}
```

ATOMICITY: Write to state.json.tmp first, then rename() (atomic on POSIX). This prevents sbh status from reading a half-written file.
STALENESS: sbh status must check last_updated and warn if > 60s old (daemon might be stalled).
PERMISSIONS: state.json readable by the user running sbh commands (0644).

